What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
(Your anonymous response to this question may be viewed by Yale College students, faculty, and advisers to aid in course selection and evaluating teaching.)
comments: How to integrate by parts and use trig substitutions. How to represent a function as an infinite series. Taylor series, Maclaurin series. How to find areas with parametric/polar formulas.
Learning calculus, although very quickly
Learned essentially AP Calculus BC, which included series, integrals, volume, area, polar, and parametric functions
I developed a better understanding of calculus basics in this course.
Calculus II topics related to Riemann Sums, solving basic and complex integrals, series, polar coordinates, and 3D shapes of revolution
How to think analytically and problem solve.
Excellent mathematical reasoning.

narratives.question_text:
What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
(Your anonymous response to this question may be viewed by Yale College students, faculty, and advisers to aid in course selection and evaluating teaching.)
comments: The strength of this course lied in the TA office hours and I felt like the problem sets were an appropriate difficulty. However, I found that the class simply wasn't that engaging.

It is good content and the textbook is good.

The course goes very quickly, so you don't get a good enough understanding. Horrible TA

Strengths: peer tutor office hours were extremely helpful; problem sets were not too stressful or demanding but questions were still challenging

Weaknesses: course material is not very applicable to real life situations or a wide variety of topics; sometimes questioned the purpose of learning a certain chapter
A strength of the course was the amount of practice and resources provided for each topic. A weakness of the course was the quick pacing of the course.
The explores, online modules, PSets, and concept checks are extremely helpful. Online resources were often more helpful and engaging than the synchronous class lessons.
I felt I struggled to connect with the material as the lectures werent as engaging.

This was the first year my professor was teaching so obviously he is still figuring out the way that works best for him, but for the course in general, I really appreciated the practice tests for each exam. They were a great way to prepare for the actual tests. Pacing is a little fast but nothing impossible to keep up with as long as you put in the effort.
Strengths: lecture notes, content, office hours. Weaknesses: minimal.
The strengths of this course were the lectures, which were engaging and had clear explanations and flow within the presentations.
more engagement and consistency amoung classes

narratives.question_text: Among the practices in this course geared toward learning during the COVID-19 pandemic, which succeeded and which could be improved? Please comment on course practices that allowed for virtual engagement. (Your anonymous response to this question may be viewed by Yale College students, faculty, and advisers to aid in course selection and evaluating teaching.)
comments: With cameras off for virtually the whole lecture, I felt disconnected during lessons. Very few people asked questions. I liked the use of breakout rooms though.

Sections were split into the same breakout rooms each class, so it gave students a chance to make friends throughout the semester. Still, the main room was very much disengaging and could have easily been a pre-recorded lecture.
The online explorations were excellent. Really great way to prep your understanding of the concepts.
I guess breakout rooms where we worked on problems as a group were nice? I wish my professor had recorded his lectures for us to rewatch.
Jamboard

The use of Jamboard was helpful in seeing different examples from outside the textbook. The problems were often more difficult and required synthesis of concepts to solve, which exposed problem areas faster for me, especially with group collaboration in breakout rooms. 

I enjoyed the polls within lectures on Zoom, which helped me see if I wasn't understanding the new material.
record lectures
